\section{Special Functions}
\begin{note}
There are a number of special built-in functions for making iterating over containers more convenient.
\begin{enumerate}
\item The \lstinline{zip} function combines two or more containers into a single container whose elements are tuples that contain the values of the original containers.
\begin{lstlisting}
>>> list(zip('hello', 'world'))
[('h', 'w'), ('e', 'o'), ('l', 'r'), ('l', 'l'), ('o', 'd')]
>>> list(zip('hello', 'world', 'hola', 'mundo'))
[('h', 'w', 'h', 'm'), ('e', 'o', 'o', 'u'), ('l', 'r', 'l', 'n'), ('l', 'l', 'a', 'd')]
>>> list(zip(range(1000), 'world'))
[(0, 'w'), (1, 'o'), (2, 'r'), (3, 'l'), (4, 'd')]
\end{lstlisting}
\item The \emph{enumerate} function creates a new container whose entries are tuples with position 0 equal to the index, and position 1 equal to the value in the original container. It is like doing a zip + range.
\begin{lstlisting}
>>> list(enumerate('hello'))
[(0, 'h'), (1, 'e'), (2, 'l'), (3, 'l'), (4, 'o')]
>>> enumerate('hello')
<enumerate object at 0x7f4521f6c220>
\end{lstlisting}
(Notice that I am using the \lstinline{list} function above only to convert the enumerate type into a list type for display.)
\end{enumerate}
\end{note}
